An index longer than the ring is a sign of low risk of cancer.
Men who have the index more than the ring are exposed to a lower risk of prostate cancer.
That is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday in the British Journal of cancer.
This may depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"our findings show that the length of the finger on a straightforward test of risk of prostate cancer, especially for males before age 60," proclaimed the co-author of the study Ros Eeles, Professor at the Institute for cancer research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine what men should undergo testing for prostate cancer, including by combining with the genetic risk aggrâvants or other factors, such as family health antécedents added Eeles.
During the period of 1994-2009 she followed with his colleagues in Britain more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer and nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the index finger of his right hand shorter than the ring.
For them, as for the 19 per cent of those who had the fingers of the same length, it was found the same likelihood of a prostate cancer.
In the case of those who had the index more than the ring the risk is, however, dropped to 33 per cent for men before 60 years the reduction of risk has risen to 87 per cent.
The length of two fingers cited - trained during the prenatal period - including different levels of sex hormones, which is exposed to the child in the womb.
A less testosterone is an index.
Previous research had shown that it is precisely the testosterone, which help in the development of a prostate cancer.
The pprofesseur vacla paces, Czech généticien renowned and former President of the Academy of Sciences, said for KTC that it is aware of this study but it seems not, apparently, that the relationship between the length of the fingers and the cancer is "completely demonstrated".
