Fight of talent to win the senior potential
The counter is great pressure.
16 students are to buy bread rolls to salmon, tomato puree and blancs-mangers.
The Technical University of Braunschweig and the car manufacturer Volkswagen invited students in design and engineering at a workshop.
In the framework of a competition of ideas, they must speak profession on the car of the future with the developers of VW, and know the firm Volkswagen.
Nowadays, many companies did not hesitate to go to the body in the competition to find best brains and engage, as Volkswagen, in a multifaceted cooperation with universities.
Their mission: to hire the most talented graduates as much as possible in the lecture halls before they enter the labour market and they are are courted by others.
And since universities do not publish statements regarding the performance of their students, it tries to identify exceptional talent in the framework of practical projects and retention.
On the second day of the workshop at the Technical University of brauschweig the automotive group amadoue talents.
A young lady from service of staff shared the pens, sweets and cards bearing the logo of Volkswagen.
She spoke of the calendar of vocational courses and jobs students young talents; it shows the paths for access to the compound of the Group.
It is Nico Chump at the Technical University of Braunschweig, who is responsible for the project with Volkswagen.
For him, there are mutual benefits for both parties: "students are in contact with the industrial sector and are gaining experience."
"the Volkswagen group, he may hear students, look more closely the serious candidates and appreciate those who enter into account as a friend."
According to Mr. sirloin, such cooperation is unusual.
What is new is the offensive with which it seeks to attract students.
"In the past, the emphasis was more on the professional project", says Mr Chump.
The fight for the conquest of new graduates will become even more bitter.
In many sectors, companies can no longer recruit their staff through a screening on a host of candidates.
But they should brag about their reliability and woo the highly skilled work force.
It is mainly graduates from the engineering who are in an excellent position to negotiate.
According to the Association of German VDI engineers, more than 40,000 engineers posts remained vacant in October.
And according to the forecasts of the VDI, a vacuum on the post of Engineer expands further.
Roman dykta goes on the hunt for talent for KPMG, the auditing firm, forensic accounting and Council.
It organizes costly events aimed at the recruitment of talent, as for example the race kpmg-race cruise, a kind of rallye-papier where competitors must find their way to the GPS coordinates.
The company will send eight and promising students next year so they walk this way in the United States.
Participants can also visit the subsidiaries of KPMG and know the company.
Who should participate is decided in advance after two selection procedures.
Only the cream of the cream of the many candidates will fly to the United States.
According to Mr. dykta, the means used for the pursuit of high potential in universities are increasingly important.
"We want to emerge from the batch through the race cruise."
"For us, a simple cruise was too little ”
For the hunter of talent that is Mr. dykta, the account appears to be.
"until now, we have been in contact with all the persons who took part last year in a similar action."
"some of them are about to complete their studies and wish to send their requests soon to our business," he says.
In addition to the direct amadouement inside the Campus, small and medium-sized enterprises are quite common in attending trade fairs where they are engaged in the hunt for brains.
"We are trying to achieve the graduates participating in the fairs."
"for example, at the Salon of solar technologies," said Ms. Sitha stübe, Director of Human Resources at solarworld, a manufacturer of photovoltaic panels.
This company located in Bonn employs about 1,500 people in Germany.
Ms. stübe is aware of the problems linked to the rotation.
Currently, 35 posts are set to contest on the site.
"at the moment, it is very difficult to fill vacancies."
"This is expensive and time-consuming," authenticity?
Another way to establish contact is to move by university professors.
Solarworld has established cooperation with various institutions of higher education, for example, the University of Fribourg.
"teachers reported that the student has the possibility to conduct training courses or write his draft end to study at home. ”
Expensive advertising campaigns are announced in the solar specialists.
It is for this reason that the company is trying to make his advertisement highlighting other qualities: personalized atmosphere, hierarchy flat and easy communication.
"often, a large group cannot do this," says Ms. stübe, Chief of Staff.
There has long been that money is no longer the main role in the search for employment.
The flexible working hours, the custody of children or good opportunities for promotion are other factors.
According to a study conducted by the great place to work Institute, solarworld ranks 55th place among the 100 best employers for Germany.
The Institute provides a table of honour of German employers.
To this end, he questioned the staff about their level of satisfaction with their work and its context while watching the framework conditions for employees.
The Chief of Staff Dr. stübe hopes that this will foster the image of society with job seekers.
"I think the candidates rely mainly with external assessments with regard to a potential employer," it declares.
Wolf Reiner Kriegler of German Academy Debba (Deutscher use branding Akademie, Debba) advises companies wishing to build a good reputation as an employer in applying a long-term strategy.
He advises clients to show more of authenticity.
And, according to Mr. Kriegler, this means primarily domestic measures.
"the best way for an employer to make attractive is through its own staff", he says.
That is, after the jargon in the sector, the internal branding strategy, i.e. the creation of the image of the employer within his own ranks.
"The met Office is the best messengers."
When it treats its employees and that they identify with the company, they are all advertising of their employer among friends and acquaintances.
"It is as if it was playing in an orchestra, ” said Mr. Kriegler.
Obama puts a brake on new oil drilling
There will be no new oil drilling in the Gulf of Mexico off the Florida coast, south-east of the United States, over the coming years.
Washington has imposed a ban a ban and, thus, permanently revoked its original plans.
Even off the Atlantic coast, new wells are currently banned.
The Secretary of the Interior Ken Salazar has made the announcement Wednesday.
It is the explosion in April, "drilling rig Deepwater Horizon" which is at the origin of this strict ban. It shall remain in effect for at least the next five years.
In response to the accident that killed 11 workers and led to the greatest environmental disaster in the United States, President Barack Obama, under pressure from the opposition and the industry, had indicated that it was willing to allow new drilling in the eastern Gulf of Mexico.
Supporters of this solution to reduce U.S. dependence on foreign countries for oil supply.
The question of who bears responsibility for the disastrous spill in the Gulf has not, to date, definitively resolved.
The British oil group, which is facing claims of billions, is at the centre of the accusations.
A commission of inquiry set up by Obama must submit its conclusions in December.
In October, the Secretary of the Interior Ken Salazar had lifted the freeze of drilling imposed after the explosion of the Platform.
Following this decision, various oil groups had immediately submitted applications for new drilling.
With stricter controls and tougher safety instructions, Obama and Salazar wants to prevent further disaster.
The competent supervisory authority, which was discredited after many accusations of corruption, is currently the subject of in-depth reform.
At the same time, Mr. Obama has pledged to remove the lucrative tax niches of gas and oil groups.
The players in this sector are now publicly warned about the fact that the flow of food in the Gulf would be significantly lower than is the case at present.
"The Government's objective is to curb the rapid growth of the sector of gas and oil," according to the results of a survey conducted in the current sector by the audit firm BDO, before the drilling ban imposed on Wednesday.
Moreover, the American Energy Alliance regret the uncertainty which characterises this sector: "nobody knows exactly what will change with the Regulation."
Investments made in support of new projects have been postponed until further notice, at the expense of growth.
Ogoniland is dry
The water flowing in the rivers is functioning; Brown, it releases a smell similar to that which exists in the petrol station: because of a large, billions of litres of crude oil have destroyed the country Ogoni in Nigeria.
Men live by theft, corruption and oil refining.
Celestine akpobari has a good intention.
"Do you not exhausted," launching the green activist to journalists for the calm: "you today still enough mud of oil before the lens of water."
The 37-year-old Nigerian tried to photograph a young depressed boueuse in water up to his chest, as well as the surrounding fat drag: this scene seems almost beautiful in the glow of water to the colour of the Rainbow.
You may not realize that the basement full of brown water of crude oil.
On the shore of the river bodo-jetty, Esther badom recounts that, once she was collecting buckets of shrimp, whole here.
But in the meantime the calm waters had completely dried up.
Five years ago there was an enormous amount of oil has bounced from a pipeline had exploded in the vast swamp.
The fishermen living in the nearby small town of Bodo must now swim for six hours to reach the fishing waters: Ogoniland, located in the heart of the Niger Delta is considered one of the most polluted in the world.
The full extent of the devastation evident when it passes through the mangrove swamps travels by rivers.
Instead of a clear water, the motor vessel heartrending brown water cradingue. Anyone who puts his hand the cut any covered with oil.
The roots of mangrove small corner of the ground as sticks of isolated réglisse. Palm trees are sadly hang their palms.
One looks in vain the clouds of birds, as it usually present in the wetlands: as soon as the outboard motor stops, a shadowy silence is approaching this paradise of once resembling a petrol station by the smell that it generates.
"what happens here, this is war against the environment," said Mr. Celestine akpobari air sad: "our life is characterized by a permanent danger in relation to health."
The comparison of war is made.
The region is home to the Ogoni people besieged a battlefield for decades: there are more than 60 years, the first European explorers have entered here; the first resistance was organized in the 1980s by the writer Ken saro-wiwa. it was performed later. In 1993, the Group shell was forced to stop its production activities in this region, because they had become very dangerous for its employees.
Even today, the return to the Ogoni countries is prohibited in this society: while more than 2 million barrels of oil daily are pumped through more than 5,000 drilling wells and 7 000 kilometres of pipelines in the whole of the Delta region, three times as great as Switzerland, the country's oil fields are tapped Ogoni, because the situation is too unstable for the oil group.
Every few hundred metres stand in water of steel tréteaux as weird sculptures: it means very affectionate "Christmas trees," the head of drilled holes.
They have up to 50 years, most are consumed by corrosion until benchmark.
Akpobari believes that a head of drilling of this nature snaps from time to time in the piece, as a constant flow of crude oil flows through the water.
According to expert estimates, more than two billion litres spilled on the ecosystem in 50 years: each year, the amount of oil equivalent to that which has passed into the sea during the accident on super-pétrolier "Exxon Valdez" 21 years ago off the coast of Alaska, one of the greatest environmental disaster in the history of humanity.
That should be the responsibility of continuing environmental pollution? The answer to this question has divided the player.
For the Group shell, sabotage and siphonage pipelines are responsible for more than 90 per cent of pollution. The environmentalists, for their part, see the explosions of warheads drilling and pipeline punctured as the main causes.
In 2008, the American scholar Richard Steiner criticized the Shell Group in Nigeria of security standards mostly less strict than anywhere else in the world: only the rate of failures of pipelines was "much higher than alleures".
Some emerging forms of mangroves in a place that, seen from afar, resembles a workshop abandoned, full of cambouis and installed outdoors: they are completely naked and covered in cambouis up to the neck.
A lamp scintille under one of the many barrels which sometimes linked to pipes, sometimes scattered without grounds on the site must be répérés: a small illegal refinery.
It warmed the crude oil into the barrel for several hours, said Michael, the team leader.
Initially, the petrol enters a receptacle through pipes, then, at the end of the conduct of drops kerosene fall and finally the diesel.
It is as well that Michael and his four friends four daily barrels of diesel 300 litres: "We reported 34 million Naira", about $22.
The inhabitants of the Delta to take advantage of the chronic shortage of fuel in the largest oil producer in sub-Saharan Africa.
Nigeria has only one refinery.
The illegal refiners can sell at a cheaper price than ridiculously low of just 40 euro cents per litre of diesel: as they acquire them free of charge.
It is offered by the "protectors" who put the network of pipelines in successful throughout the country of the Ogoni. According to the experts, the country loses this way at least 16 million gallons of crude oil in the Niger Delta.
Only a small part quite insignificant to the raw material is temporarily stored illegally cleansed: organized crime networks which are also among its members of politicians and senior military officers, responsible for the lion's share of the tankers and dumping on the world market.
The activist akpobari considers that the debate on the question of whether to award the environmental disaster or rather subversive activities in the public or the mode of production lax is purely academic.
"If the oil companies were not seen as intruders and if the foundations of the lives of the fishermen were not so deeply destroyed, there would be no sabotage or theft and illegal refineries."
