Mysterious earth-moving work
The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) provides further guidance regarding a nuclear programme developed by Syria.
But this country refuses to take a position on this subject, still less to submit to inspections by the Agency.
On the night of 5 to 6 September 2007, around midnight, at least four (F-15 fighter aircraft attacked a mysterious Israeli building cubic shape on Syrian territory.
It is situated on the banks of the Euphrates, the largest city near located 30 kilometres is Dair as-sur.
His name appears in documents of the IAEA, as it is a question of the Syrian nuclear reactor allegedly built with help from North Korea in parallélépipède stone, hidden in a valley marked by the absence of electric power.
According to a briefing of the intelligence services of the United States, the CIA, dating from the end of April 2008, the current reactor, known as the neighbouring locality, el-kibar, would be able to produce plutonium for the manufacture of atomic weapons.
However, this technique is valid since the 1950s.
The CIA has shown a video presentation with satellite images are blurred.
Through the computer-assisted animation, it indicated the likely location of each component of the reactor before the destruction of the plant represents a miniature copy of the North Korean model of the Yongbyon nuclear facility.
In addition, it submitted photographs showing the building located in close proximity and internally.
It seems that the reactor was about to be put into service, but it was not yet equipped with fuel rods.
Today, more than three years after the Israeli bombing, it has barely more information at the time, and with time the mystery grows increasingly.
The former US President George W. Bush recently revealed in his memoirs that prior to this attack, the CIA was sure that Syria had built a nuclear reactor at el-kibar but had peu' indices showing the country "was an active programme of nuclear weapons".
Some intelligence agents in Europe tend to be more cautious and speak only of an alleged "reactor", even if they consider the introduction of the CIA as "plausible".
The lack of evidence, as well as to the IAEA.
Asked about how it ensures that it is dealing with a nuclear reactor, a senior diplomat Nations gave a terse response in been in affirming that the IAEA had "sufficient documents to ask questions".
The Syrians have certainly removed with haste the rubble of "unused military building" and conducted a systematic levelling the ground.
However, in June 2008, a team of IAEA experts led by former Chief Inspector Oli Heinonen, discovered at el-kibar traces of uranium produced by men.
In addition, IAEA received through a Member State satellite images of commercial providers showing the moment that followed directly the attaque. it seems that they are more eloquent than those presented by the CIA.
However, these photos are not available on the market because the anonymous sponsor, perhaps Israel, has gained in exclusivity.
It is therefore impossible for the IAEA to establish their authenticity objectively.
Syria has always maintained that she had never made a secret atomic programme and that it had not built reactor.
Damascus maintains that the uranium found at the site of weapons used by Israel.
But the IAEA has rejected that argument after The PM analysis as an implausible.
Since that time, Damascus denies any discussion on this, as on the satellite images.
In addition, Syria does not allow inspectors to carry out a second inspection on the site of el-kibar and denial of access to the rubble of buildings destroyed by the bomb.
But even Israel retains a stubborn silence.
Confirming the official position, Ehud Olmert, then Prime Minister at the time of the attack, said recently: "We will never comments on this subject".
It is as well that the investigation on this matter has been dragging on since June 2008 without reaching an outcome and that it "is increasingly becoming a serious problem for the credibility of the Agency ”, as recognized in a senior Western diplomat in service at IAEA headquarters in Vienna, ultimately it is a serious violation of the Treaty for the Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons.
IAEA considers that to make progress, we must clarify the existence of three other facilities which must have "a substantive report" with the alleged reactor.
Until now, the inspectors have not indicated what facilities here, and what is their function or are suspected to contain.
According to information published by the newspaper Süddeutsche Zeitung ', they are known within IAEA respectively under the names of Marj as-Sultan masyaf iskandariayah, and also the name of neighbouring towns.
The Independent Institute for Science and International Security (International Institute for Science and International Security in Washington has identified these localities and discovered on satellite images a complex near masyaf which would most probably be a suspicious objects.
It is possible that he is in a military base or directly adjacent to it; this is exactly why Syria refuses access of the three sites to IAEA inspectors.
In Vienna, it contends that the Syrians feared that the inspection group is in fact spies who were sent on behalf of the United States by IAEA to spy on its military installations.
Indeed, it is the information provided by the American secret agents who attracted the attention of nuclear inspectors.
The IAEA provides information, including satellite photos indicating that vehicles have been shuttling between the three locations and the stone parallélépipède to carry substances.
A senior Western diplomat in Vienna said that at least one of the facilities could "serve to fuel production".
There would be "no indications concerning sensitive activities", such as enrichment and reprocessing of uranium; processes that are essential to the production of atomic weapons.
This reactor is certainly working through not enriched uranium.
Nevertheless, there is a plausible assumptions on the fundamental questions: where should have come and where uranium or plutonium separated later needed to manufacture a bomb.
It is unclear whether the rubble, which could hide traces of great value, were stored at the three sites.
When the hundreds of truckloads of Earth will have disappeared, no one has information on the location of the rubble.
For the IAEA, it is unlikely that Syria has been considered in 1998 the salt mine of al-tibni, located only a few miles from el-kibar, across the Euphrates, to see if it can agree to the storage of radioactive waste.
Analysis of recent satellite photos for the famous magazine Jane's Intelligence Review, former inspector of the IAEA, Mr. Robert Kelley has established a link between them and the reactor in question.
The satellite photos show that Syria has begun work in the three suspect sites and pumped huge containers where the IAEA began demanding access to these places.
It is possible that this is a coincidence, but that has not helped to avert suspicion.
As it is said in diplomatic circles that the IAEA has spent several months to develop a plan for the inspections to be carried out. This plan should allow Syria to preserve any military secrets. Only the time invested shows how much interest the Inspectors in this case.
Meanwhile, Damascus has also made a mockery of this proposal.
A year ago, while Western diplomats in Vienna had not reported the destruction of the reactor, the emergency would not be brought to this case, argues, for example, Glyn Davies, the Ambassador of the United States, which mentions a few months ago what is known as the special inspections, one of the most powerful Atomic Agency to implement its controls.
The Director of the IAEA, Yukiya Amano, who has had to offer these inspections, has already talked about "an option that I am open to the future," but it still hesitate.
This means a huge risk: on the one hand, it requires a majority on the Board of Governors of the IAEA and a good number of 35 countries which are represented there have no desire to see the situation escalate.
On the other hand, as the diplomat who gives réflechir: "at this point, if in the end they did not find anything".
