The democratic routine
Support for democracy in Latin America continues to increase, as well as to private enterprise.
Crime has become a greater concern than unemployment.
And Brazil is seen as more influence than the United States in a large part of the region.
These are some of the conclusions of the latest Latinobarómetro poll taken in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Given that the survey has been carried out regularly since 1995, it tracks changes in attitudes in the region.
Two interrelated aspects reflected in the results of the poll, conducted in September and early October.
The first is the sunny enough mood of Latin America.
The second is the growing attitudes towards stability, democracy and its key institutions.
Support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries on the Pacific rim of South America (see table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6 per cent per year since 2002, support for democracy has increased to a minimum of 40 per cent in 2005 to 61% this year.
It has also grown in Mexico, where the economy rebounded after it suffered a sharp drop in production last year.
But only about half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries of the region, are convinced democrats, which lowers the regional average (see table 2).
Some 44 per cent of respondents in the region were satisfied with how their democracy works in practice; it is the same figure as last year but with a sharp increase on the 25 per cent in 2001 (see figure 3)
Some 34 per cent said that they had confidence in Parliament of their countries and 45 per cent in their Government, the same as last year in both cases; but this is a significant increase compared to 2003 (17 per cent and 24 per cent).
Ten years ago, the economic problems in Latin America have undermined support for democracy.
If this was good during the global financial crisis, it is certainly due to the fact that many countries in Latin America have experienced only a brief recession and have benefited from a strong recovery.
In addition, a social security network has helped to protect the poor.
(the United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty had increased only slightly in 2009 and has fallen again this year to 32 per cent.)
But the mood varies considerably from one country to another (see chart 4).
The good economic performance of Brazil and the popularity of its outgoing President, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, a widely shared sense of progress
What is more rare in Mexico and Central America, where the recession has been more severe and where violent crimes escalated.
This is only the second time since the poll began that more respondents across Latin America as a whole have cited the crime rather than unemployment as the most important issue in their countries (see table 5).
Approximately 31 per cent say that they or one of their own had been the victim of a criminal act in the past year; however, this figure is declining compared to 38 per cent last year and is the lowest since 1995.
A more robust economic performance was reflected in the surge of support for private enterprise and market economy: approximately 71% of respondents in the region say that private enterprise is indispensable for development, against 56 per cent in 2007 (see chart 6).
Some 58% think that the market economy is the only system that will make their developed country, against 47 per cent last year.
Interestingly, 62 per cent of respondents in Venezuela are of this opinion (and 80% support private enterprise); even if their left-wing president, Hugo Chavez, expropriating many private companies.
Brazil is the greatest leader in the region, mentioned by 19 per cent of respondents (compared with 18 per cent last year), followed by the United States (9 per cent, unchanged from last year) and Venezuela (9 per cent, down 11 per cent since last year)
But the United States is seen as the most influential by respondents in Mexico and much of Central America, while Venezuela enjoys this distinction in Ecuador, in the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
