Nobody expected to be perfect for general elections in Haiti on November 28.
But this was much worse than the "outsiders" who wanted to help the stricken country and plunged in fear.
It presented the ballot boxes and voting, ballot papers scattered in the goutières, polling stations were ransacked and intimidation
Polling stations opened late in the evening.
Many hatïens, including many who were displaced following the earthquake of January, roamed the neighborhood to find where to vote.
Some of them were eventually abandoned.
A dozen presidential candidates, including several frontrunners, have condemned the alleged fraud and have called for the cancellation of the election.
Protests, sometimes violent, exploded across the country.
Nevertheless, Edmond Mulet, the top official in Haiti, the United Nations, sees the event as "an election fairly good in many respects".
Observers from the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community said cautiously that they "believed that these irregularities, as serious as they are, were necessarily invalidated the process".
In other words, the show continues.
The electoral authority, whose opponents are beholden to René Préval, outgoing President unpopular, and its candidate, Jude Célestin, must announce preliminary results on 7 December.
The long-awaited second round is scheduled for January.
Any hope in the election is not lost.
The two opposition candidates, Michel martelly, a rap musician and Mirlande Manigat, a former First Lady, have withdrawn their initial appeal for the vote to be annulled.
But there may be problems if Mr. Célestin, who has little or no discernible support among voters, is declared by the electoral authority as having reached the second Toura reached the second round.
With a cholera epidemic raging, and more than 1 million earthquake survivors who are still living in tents, it was feared that participation would be.
Accordingly, many haitïens wanted to vote but were prevented from doing so because of the disruption.
Almost 250,000 identity cards necessary to vote, were not yet distributed shortly before the election.
The issue is important.
Donors see the election of a legitimate Government and people as an important step in the reconstruction of Haiti.
And thus, it is clear, Haitians are doing themselves.
The tips of his toes to the Centre
The weeks after becoming suddenly widow, Cristina Fernández, President of Argentina, has benefited from a wave of sympathy from the public who has improved his approval rate of 20 points, to over 50 per cent, its highest level since it was elected in 2007.
However, transforming it into a successful campaign for a second term at an election next year could depend on the choice of Ms Fernández, visibly in mourning, that it would abandon the intransigence of her deceased husband's predecessor and former political partner, Néstor Kirchner.
And, in this regard, the signs are still confused.
Mr. Kirchner, who has continued to manage the economic policy, even after his wife succeeded him as President, used to prepare budgets that underestimated tax revenues, economic growth and inflation.
This has enabled the first couple to spend the extra income at will.
The Government of Ms. Fernández has lost its majority in Congress last year, on paper.
But the opposition is divided, and the situation has descended into disarray following the death of Mr Kirchner of a heart attack on 27 October.
Some of the dissident members of the ruling Peronist movement joined Ms. Fernández.
But after the chaotic meetings (where one member was struck in the face by one of its peers and others have accused the Government of corruption), Congress did not approve the budget for 2011.
"I am not going to compete," said the President.
Currently, the 2010 budget will be implemented next year, leaving the President yet more flexibility to spend at will.
The economy overheating widely: it is likely to grow by nearly 9 per cent this year.
The official rate of inflation is now 11.1 per cent but many private estimates and the wage demands of unions, see this figure close to 30 per cent.
Mr. Kirchner, who took office in 2003 when Argentina feared an economic collapse, has made a priority of the growth and poverty reduction, rather than the control of inflation.
It has refused to deal with the IMF, it has harassed the private sector and served the INDEC, the Statistical Office, which conducted the forgery of official statistics on inflation.
Ms. Fernández now can mitigate these policies?
It called for talks between private companies and union leaders.
And officials say they want to limit the salary increases next year to 6 per cent.
The economy has been boosted by high world prices for agricultural exports from Argentina.
But inflation has eroded the boost to growth following a sharp devaluation in 2002.
Perhaps that is why Ms. Fernández shows signs of wanting to re-establish financial relations of Argentina to the rest of the world.
This year, the Government has concluded an agreement with bondholders who had rejected an earlier restructuring of debt on which Argentina had not adjusted its targets in 2001.
Now Ms Fernández seems to be edging towards an agreement with creditor Governments grouped in the Paris Club, to which it owes some $6.7 billion.
The Kirchners have always insisted on the fact that this could involve monitoring by the IMF, as is customary.
But last month, Amado boudou, the economy minister, announced that the Fund would provide a "technical assistance" to design a new national consumer price index; what appears to be a prelude to the clean-up of the INDEC.
It is not clear whether Mrs. Fernández wants to remain in politics beyond the end of his term, now that her husband was no longer near her.
If she does, she needs to win the support of the middle class, among which the kirchnerisme is very advocated.
When Argentines will be returned from their summer holidays in March, the wave of sympathy for it has receded.
If it wants to win another election, it will have to decide whether or not to repudiate, noise, many of the policies of her husband.
