A microbe tolerant arsenic raises the possibility of new forms of life on Earth, or elsewhere.
The discovery of a strange bacteria, which can use arsenic as one of its nutrients, broadens the scope for finding new forms of life on Earth, and perhaps beyond.
Although researchers have discovered the unusual bacterium here on Earth, they say it shows that life has opportunities beyond the major elements that were considered essential.
"This body has a dual capacity."
"It can be expanded with either the phosphorus, either with arsenic."
"that is why it is very special, even though it is far from being a form of life really foreign", "commented Paul Davies, C. W. of the University of Arizona State, co-author of the report in Thursday's online edition of the journal Science.
Six major components have long been considered essential for life: carbon, hydrogen, oxygen, nitrogen, phosphorus and sulphur.
But the researchers found that the bacteria was discovered in the Mono Lake in California, is able to continue to grow after replacing phosphorus by arsenic.
"one wonders what is still possible," said Ariel Anbar D. of the State University of Arizona, co-author of the report.
The discovery is important in the search for life beyond Earth because researchers must be able to recognize the life, to know what life is like, said Anbar.
The study focuses on a microbe found on Earth.
However, the announcement of a press conference to discuss the matter, which has not disclosed the details of the discovery, has generated widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could disclose the discovery of a life extraterrestre.
This has not been the case.
The discovery "shows that in other planetary environments, organizations might be able to use other elements to actuate the biochemistry and that the whole" standard "elements, that we are absolutely necessary for life, could not be determined," commented Charles cockell, Professor at the Institute of Planetary Research and spacial, Open University, Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
"This work is new, because it shows the substitution of one element to another basic Biochemistry and biochemical structure," added cockell.
This was not a casual discovery.
Felisa wolfe-simon Institute for NASA astrology, who led the study, has chosen the Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar; thus, it was speculated that a microbe presentation to the two substances might be able to replace one with the other.
"toxic arsenic is mainly because its chemical behaviour is very similar to that of the phosphorus."
"Accordingly, the agencies were struggling to distinguish these components separately."
"But the arsenic is sufficiently different to that it is not exactly as phosphorus; he got inside, and, somehow, the gum out of our biological machine," explained Anbar.
The researchers found the bacteria known as gfaj-1 and exposed to increasing concentrations of arsenic, which she has been able to adapt and grow.
The microbe grows better with phosphorous but the fact that he can live with arsenic in place raises the possibility that a form of life using arsenic may occur naturally, either on land or on another planet and the Moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, Assistant Professor of Microbiology at the University of Florida, said that the idea that arsenic could be replaced by the phosphorus, was not new; but nothing has ever shown that it could walk.
Arsenic was more frequent at the beginning of the existence of the Earth, she said; so, researchers have speculated that the first life forms could use it.
This suggests that there may be other ways of life, not just how life on Earth was formed at the beginning, "said foster, who was not part of the research team of wolfe-simon.
The research was funded by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institute of Health.
