Prosecutors did not Senator Ensign inculperont
Prosecutors from the Ministry of Justice have lifted the criminal charges brought on Senator John Ensign, arising out of a case related to an assistant to a former campaign and its efforts to obtain a lobbying work for the husband of the woman, have anoncé Wednesday, lawyers for the senator.
The decision brings to a close the most serious legal threat faced by Mr. Ensign, republican of Nevada, who was seen as a possible Republican candidate for the 2012 presidential until the scandal surrounding his case made national headlines last year and undermine his career.
The Office of Mr. Ensign said he was "very pleased" with the decision, the result of a survey a year ago.
The Senator could still be subject to disciplinary action by the Senate Committee on Ethics.
Lawyers for Mr. Ensign said that the Ministry of Justice had "informed that Senator Ensign was no longer a subject of the investigation and that it had no intention of maintaining any charges against him in this case."
The Justice Department declined to comment on this subject.
The announcement came as a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Ministry of Justice, according to which there was significant evidence indicating that Mr. Ensign allegedly conspired to violate a ban on lobbying federal criminal.
Interviews, e-mails and other documents, first reported in October 2009 in the New York Times, showed that Mr. Ensign helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, to obtain a lucrative lobbying to win the silence of Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, in case of Senator with it.
Ms. Hampton once served as Treasurer in a campaign to Ensign.
Mr. Ensign has contacted a number of donors to find work for Mr. Hampton and, secondly, it has defended their rights after they called Mr. Hampton for lobbying for them, according to documents and interviews.
Given that Mr. Hampton had recently been a friend of Mr. Ensign, he was banned for a year by law from lobbying his former employer or the Senate as a whole.
The ethics experts have argued that the unusual agreement between Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were friends before the case, seems inconsistent with the prohibition of so-called revolving door of lobbying.
According to the evidence, which was made public, "there appears to be a prima facie evidence of a conspiracy to violate, and substantive violations of the Act of the revolving door," said Stanley brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defense of customers of an investigation by the Government.
Although the judge of the Ministry has refused to explain the reasoning behind the decision in the case of Ensign, Mr. brand and other ethics lawyers have said that the Ministry appeared to be wary of political prosecutions after a number of setbacks cashed high level by the public integrity section, including the decision last year to abandon the charges against former Senator Ted Stevens accused of misconduct proceedings.
Federal prosecutors have clearly afraid to take up arms, said Melanie Sloan, Executive Director of citizens for responsibility and ethics in Washington, a group that has received several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
"This basically says high-ranking Government officials can now took the laws don't apply to them," she added.
Paul coggins, lead counsel for Mr. Ensign, said in an interview that he had received on Monday a telephone call from the Prosecutor of the Ministry of Justice and a follow-up to the next day, saying that the Ministry did not seek charges against his client.
The team of lawyers for Mr. Ensign had cooperated with prosecutors to try to persuade them that the Senator, as his Office reiterated Wednesday, in a statement, "had acted in accordance with the law. ”
Mr. coggins refused to specify the legal arguments it had made to the Public Prosecutor's Office.
"I am not comfortable to go into the details of my discussions with the Ministry of Justice, except to say that we believe they made the right decision," at-il said.
Last month, the Federal Commission for Elections decided to drop an investigation following a complaint by the independent Ethics Group, arguing that the payment of 96.000 $by the parents of Mr. Ensign to Hampton violated federal election law.
The Electoral Commission said that it did not have enough evidence to prove that the money was anything but a gift.
NV energy, Nevada a large company that has long supported Senator, is a company for which Mr. Ensign helped Mr. Hampton find lobbying work.
An e-mail sent in December 2008 showed that, after the company hosted Mr. Hampton as a lobbyist, the Chief of Staff to Mr. Ensign, John Lopez, has communicated with Mr. Hampton and told him that he "martelait" the Ministry of the Interior on an issue in dispute.
Mr. Ensign also attended a lunch with Mr. Hampton and another client of Nevada, allegiant air, and it requested the Secretary of Transportation to set a meeting on behalf of the airline after Mr. Hampton to lobbying.
When news of the affair emerged last year, Mr. Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned his leadership post to rank fourth in the Senate Republican.
Having kept a low profile for several months, Mr. Ensign said two weeks ago that he intended to run for a third term in the Senate.
In announcing that Mr. Ensign was not the target of a criminal investigation, his spokeswoman, Jennifer Cooper, said the Senator had hoped that the Ethics Committee quickly follow the example of the Ministry of Justice and put an end to its investigation.
Senator Ensign is pleased to continue its hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada, she said.
The appeal of Cheshire pointera to Twitter
Half a dozen of them were in the process of tapping away in the rows of the courtroom.
They sent all the minutes of reports of horrific testimony via Twitter.
At the end, the defense has said that there are more than 140,000 messages on the trial of the case of rape and children tied to their beds in a house that had been set on fire.
On Thursday, the trial largely followed by Steven J. Hayes, who was convicted of killing three members of a family in Cheshire, Connecticut, should lead to a formal end where the judge imposes the death penalty, approved by the Board of Examiners.
But lawyers for Mr. Hayes had already file of evidence to the court describing the arguments of appeal to the courts for years.
That is provocative, it is that the intense coverage of the trial — as well as the widespread use and extended by journalists on Twitter — have created "a circus atmosphere," saturation if widespread and instantaneous incendiary details, that the jury had been influenced by the passions of the public.
The request could push the appeals judges to discuss the question of whether new technologies require new rules in the courtrooms.
"I have made the experience during the trial; I think there is a real danger, the introduction of new technologies in the courtrooms, infringes on the Rights of the person to a fair trial," said Thomas J. Ullmann, the lawyer for Mr. Hayes, chief lawyer.
The trial judge Jon C. Blue State Superior Court, a laconiquement rejected the claims in the judgment last week, saying that the media were "carefully monitored" and that there was no evidence that the jury was driven by passion.
But that does not seem to be the last word on the matter.
Courts of Appeal shall recognize for decades that media coverage of high-profile cases may raise questions about the fairness of the trial.
In a judgement of 1966, the United States Supreme Court has overturned the conviction of a ostéopathe Cleveland, Dr. Sam Sheppard, for the murder of his wife, supporting in its decision that there was an "atmosphere of Carnival at trial" because of the media.
The crime is considered by some to have been the inspiration for the television broadcast, and the film "The fugitive."
Some lawyers have said that the court of appeal for review before half a century later, the conviction of Mr. Hayes can be strange given the argument that new rules could be necessary to manage the media from the courtroom, unforeseen at the time of the case of Dr Sheppard.
"There is a general right to worry about the impact of new media" in the large-scale trial, said John J. Donohue III, a professor at the Stanford Law school who has studied the death penalty in Connecticut and wrote a report that she had been arbitrarily applied.
Professor Donohue asserts that some judges of appeal could be intrigued by the idea that the limitation of instantaneous communication from courtrooms could allow fairer trial.
The case of Twitter is only one among many others described by lawyers for Mr. Hayes, likely to be discussed during the years; what is delaying the execution.
Defence lawyers also claim, for example, that Mr. Hayes suffered an injury when the judge Blue refused to allow them to test the reaction of potential jurors in their showing photos of macabre crime scenes in the selection of the jury.
Some jurors said they were horrified by the images of victims, Jennifer hawke-petit, 48, and her daughters, hayley, 17, and Michaela, 11 years ago.
Defence lawyers say they will also contest the constitutionality of the death penalty and they will argue that the judge had unjustly expelled one juror, who had been critical to the prosecutors and that he was improperly put pressure for a verdict by taking the unusual decision to persuade the jury to deliberate in a weekend.
Jurors have not been hijacked.
But their arguments on the effect of the intense media coverage of the trial could be the greatest source of interest.
They noted in a challenge against the verdict, filed last month that the case dominated the media scene in Connecticut and was discussed during the election campaign by the candidates for governor and the U.S. Senate.
They have maintained that the computer media continued to fan the flames of the emotion of the case.
"The stampede of daily tweets of media cameras and journalists to the Palace of Justice," the lawyers wrote, "do resembled nothing had been seen earlier here in New Haven, and perhaps even at the national level."
Their focus on the coverage of the Twitter system is controversial.
In interviews, some journalists have stated that the assertion that the more incendiary instantaneous news releases issued more slowly, was a much diminished luddiste view that the policy of the Court for the media coverage of future trials.
But some lawyers have said that the appeal courts étaitent often lured by arguments that the social and technological change required an adaptation by the courts.
Lawyers for Mr. Hayes insisted on this claim.
In their case, they refer to the decision of the Supreme Court of 1966, which had overturned the conviction of Dr Sheppard because of media coverage of the trial and they said they invoqueraient need new rules for the new media.
"this case," écrivaient-ils "represents the Sheppard v. Maxwell of the 21st century."
Civility can it bring the divisions?
After a campaign marked by the invective and negativity, a minimum level of civility broke out in Washington this week.
Was this a harbinger of a genuine bipartisan cooperation towards the front or a time illusory before the rapid return to the partisan fight in the capital?
The meeting on Tuesday between President Obama and the leaders of Congress has produced no breakthrough on the major issues to be addressed during the session of the "lame duck".
But clearly, there was at least a polite discussion of the differences of the two parties, as well as the recognition of their shared responsibility to govern rather than another episode where each camp wanted to score rating vacuum points. item supporter.
The public meeting on Wednesday, the Commission on the deficit, the President has been equally civilized, despite political differences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created a mutual respect across the ideological divide; but which, however, still divides members.
It is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
The two parties are now in a trial period and put to the test in order to obtain evidence of cooperation and compromise, while trying to evaluate the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters for a renewed partisan war.
That is why the meeting Tuesday, and the subsequent comments were unveiled a minimum requirements or charges.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too big and too deep to suggest a rapid change of the climate that has existed in the past two years.
Whether taxation, spending, health care, or the rights, both parties remain at the mile distance.
However, the November election had moderate Washington, at least in the short term.
"There is no doubt that things have changed on the tone," said Pete wehner, a member of the Bush administration, now with the Center for Ethics and public policy.
"It is inevitable after the election.
The elections are partisan passions, and then they estomptent.
That is good. "
On some issues, especially those on the agenda of the session of "lame duck", the Republicans and Democrats had no choice but to find a solution.
The Bush tax cuts expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favour of it.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve a part or the whole of a permanent or temporary basis.
Similarly, a compromise is possible on the extension of unemployment benefits, not least because the Republicans can't afford to give the impression that they are in favour of tax cuts for the rich, while denying unemployment benefits to workers without jobs.
After the meeting Tuesday at the White House, more optimism hangs on a possible agreement on issues raised during the session on the "lame duck", with the ratification of the Covenant "new start".
But William Galston put it, of the Brookings Institution, warns that fruitful cooperation on the most pressing issues of the session "lame duck" ménera does not lead to a better understanding between the two parties when the 112th Congress convenes in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is likely, if not inevitable.
"Once things that need to be made are, the psychology in the short term will revert to a confrontation," he said.
Wehner also expressed widespread scepticism that civility would lead to genuine cooperation.
"I think most of what happens between now and 2012 as a pré-spectacle or a shadow-boxing compared to the main event in 2012, at-il said.
The reasons are closely related to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and the electorate tea who contributed to its establishment.
However, Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know that they must try to live up to their promises to reduce public spending and to repeal the new health care law.
These partisan positions are already clear in the first reactions to the recommendations of the Commission of the deficit, which includes reform of the tax code and to increase certain taxes, raising the retirement age and cutting costs.
The Co-Chairmen Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles chose one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and have imposed on themselves, the issue of the shortfall on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the Committee, composed of 18 members, to make their plan as a formal recommendation, and they have struggled to reach that number.
The greatest resistance remains among the elected members of the group; this suggests that there is on tax matters, at least today, few grounds or willingness to compromise.
Galston put it foresees two phases in the fighting between the White House and Republicans in Congress.
The first will come next year in the form of clashes supporters, given that Republicans challenged Obama on budget, tax and health care; and then be followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What is the cause of change?
Public opinion.
There is ample evidence that, despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still wants to see the two parties to work together.
If the confrontation leads to an impasse, as in 1995, when the two parties will observe closely the public reaction.
That will be tried in loss should change course and find compromises.
But this would be an optimist.
The partisanship and polarization are higher today than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a more ideological difference between Obama and the Republicans in Congress that there was between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans.
At the same time, supporters of both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a larger election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civility exposed this week could be appreciated by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on the part of both parties to find common ground on the issues that divide them.
The American documents disclosed describe Moscow as a haven of corruption
The town is in the hands of a "kleptocracy ” and moved up to the Kremlin part of bribes and money of protection that it collects, reported to the American Embassy in Russia in a note in February.
The police and the Federal Security Service are reaping enormous racketeering that help explain the high cost of living in Moscow, he said.
They collect money not only to legitimate businesses but also of organized criminal groups.
Each layer of bureaucracy - that Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called the "vertical of power" - takes its share money snakes to the top of the scale.
The memo, which was sent to Washington as Ambassador John beyrle, was posted Wednesday by WikiLeaks on its web site.
The note is based on sources whose names had been purged.
It was at that time was still Mayor Yuri Luzhkov, Moscow; and it is largely responsible for corruption.
He was dismissed in October by President Dmitry Medvedev but there has since been little traces of cleaning.
Luzhkov, and his wife, Elena batourina, who owns a construction company, have always denied the accusations of corruption over the years; and he won a libel trial on those charges.
In September, he told a Russian television channel, where he was questioned about a documentary suggesting he was corrupt: "This is crazy, it is to build, is anything."
Russians believe, by an overwhelming majority, that their society is corrupt; according to the polls.
But it is unusual to find the information contained in a report of Embassy; and it is incredible that this would be to diplomats from a foreign country to do so.
The direct link between the Government of the city of Moscow and Crime has led some people in the name of "dysfunctional" and to affirm that the Government functioned more as a kleptocracy that a Government ", according to the notes of the Embassy.
"criminal elements enjoy" krysha "(a term used in the criminal world / the mafia, which literally means" roof "or protection) which passes through the police, the Federal Security Service (FSB), the Ministry of the Interior (MVD) and the Office of the Prosecutor, as well as across the bureaucracy of the Government of the city of Moscow.
"analysts to identify a three-tier structure in the criminal world."
"Luzhkov is the Summit."
"the FSB and MVD militias are the second level."
"Finally, ordinary criminals and corrupt inspectors are at the lowest level."
"It is an inefficient system in which the criminal groups fills a gap in some areas where the city does not provide certain services."
The report indicates that the FSB has more money from big business and that the police are targeting small.
A source, he said, "explained that the Moscow business owners included that it was preferable to obtain protection of the FSB and MVD (rather than organized crime groups), not only because they have more weapons, more resources and more power than the criminal groups, but they are also protected by the law. ”
"that is why the application of protection by the criminal gangs is not so high."
The note said that, although the collection of money should be extended, protection itself can be uneven; even those who pay are sometimes subjected to arrest.
Those who do not pay their cases are rapidly closing under one pretext or another.
Medvedev has referred several times to the fight against corruption, but he admitted that little progress.
The note of the Embassy transmits documents referring to men who make suitcases full of money, probably until the Kremlin.
"in its fight against corruption, Medvedev is bureaucrats," said in a recent interview Gueorgui satarov, Director of "The indem think tank in Moscow."
"but it is part of the bureaucracy.
"It is not part of a political class because they do not exist in Russia."
Without the policy, without objection, without separation of powers, he said, corruption is inevitable.
According to the indem, costs of corruption would amount to the scale of Russia as a whole, to more than $300 billion a year.
The country has been ranked 154th in a recent poll on the overall perception of corruption by the non-governmental organization Transparency International (countries are classified at least to most corrupt).
The disclosure of the note of the American Embassy, which was achieved yesterday, late in the evening, Moscow time, remuera with certainty of discontent within the Russian Government; although Luzhkov can be blamed, to a certain extent, the failures of Moscow, this could be the opportunity for the Kremlin to show that it is in the process of solving the problem.
