"The problem is the fact that it is our interaction, important factor of domestic policy in this country, he says.
"but to be honest with you, we thought that it would be done with such arrogance, such pressure and, you know, in opposition to the ethics."
Veterans of the Khmer Rouge forced to confront the past
In a poorly lit classroom with barricades decrepit of poor quality, the Director of the secondary school in Anlong Veng referred to the man who had constructed, the last head of the Khmer Rouge, Ta Mok.
"everyone here love Ta Mok."
"It was a good leader; and he cared for his people," said Sreng KOR my, aged 42.
Known as "the butcher" for its brutality, when he was the head of the Khmer Rouge commander, remains popular in this isolated stronghold of former Khmer Rouge in north-west Cambodia where it has built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure; and where thousands of former soldiers of the Organization still live today.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered to the Government, the longstanding loyalty is finally challenged at Anlong Veng.
In April, a local forum truth and reconciliation has enabled victims to respond publicly to people who had participated in the scheme.
In June, the Government has distributed a manual high school, for the first time, teaches the history of the Khmer Rouge to children of its former soldiers.
And in July, a Cambodian court, jointly conducted with the United Nations, delivered its first award for a former member of the Khmer Rouge, condemning, in 35 years, the former head of the notorious torture centre of Tuol Sleng, Kaing khek IEV, better known as "Duch".
In this situation, anxiety has increased among the former Khmer Rouge fighters in Anlong Veng, complicating the efforts for reconciliation and their wills to reintegrate in Cambodian society.
"There is resentment and fear among the former Khmer Rouge, but they are powerless to do anything," said youk Chhang, Director of the Documentation Center of Cambodia, an independent body that conducts research on the regime.
"for them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil."
"The situation creates divisions within families."
During the reign of the Khmer Rouge in Cambodia from 1975 to 1979, about 1.7 million people were executed or died of starvation, disease and overwork.
When the Vietnamese invaded and toppled the Government of Pol pot-unis in 1979, the rest of the regime and its army have fled to Cambodia's border with Thailand.
Here, they have launched an insurgency which lasted until the last movements of a visit in December 1998.
Although Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary ran the guerrillas from their base in the mountains west of Cambodia and in the jungle, Ta Mok was preparing a response to Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a peace agreement sponsored by the United Nations has led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began to defect to the Government, culminating with the capitulations of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998 and Ta Mok, who had held Head, was captured by Government forces in 1999 in the Dangrek mountains near.
He died in a prison in Phnom Penh in 2006 while awaiting trial.
Without their benefactors, most of the former Khmer Rouge fighters have sunk in abject poverty, common in rural areas of Cambodia; and many of those who remain nostalgic for the movement.
Although a few elite officers Khmer Rouge have kept their posts in local leader in exchange for the weapons, it is farmers, unskilled low rank and file.
"These people have received very little follow-up after the capitulation," said Sok Leang Centre for Justice and Reconciliation, which organizes public forums throughout Cambodia, including Anlong Veng.
"they are saturated with the agrarian utopian ideology."
"they were raised in a context where business is an alien concept."
SOR Lim, a 55-year-old, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, has fought in the jungle around Anlong Veng before settling in 1998 as poor rice grower.
"life under the Khmer Rouge was good," he said.
"Ta Mok feeds the world."
But now, life is difficult, because we need to meet our own needs. "
The Khmer Rouge Tribunal has also caused worries here.
The Court should, at the beginning of next year, to begin the trial of Khieu Samphan, Nuon Chea, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Minister Khmer Rouge.
The Tribunal's mandate is to try senior leaders and those most responsible for the crimes, but it has not said whether it continued beyond these four cases.
There should be more to calm fears at Anlong Veng.
Recent media speculation turned to im chaem, aged 64 years, the former head of district in the Province of Banteay Meanchey under the reign of the Khmer Rouge in the 1970s.
In 2007, she said the researchers of the Documentation Centre of Cambodia that it had supervised the construction of the dam of Trapeang thma, a project where thousands of forced labourers were killed.
Recently, on a hot night, im chaem labour returned to the field near her wooden house on pilotis, on a dirt road, outside of Anlong Veng.
While the sun cast long shadows on the grass, im dried chaem refused to discuss his past in the Khmer Rouge.
If the Court the called, she said, she would refuse to go there.
"Cambodia is peaceful and stable," at-elle said.
"If there was more prosecutions, there will be war."
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who defected from the Khmer Rouge in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that instability would occur if the Tribunal had several suspects; although the experts and historians dispute this.
"Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past at-il said.
But dealing with the past is all that Cambodia is to move forward, said youk Chhang, the documentation centre.
"reconciliation in Khmer language is to reconnect the broken pieces, he says.
"We must put the pieces together so that we can understand."
The Centre has produced the first manual approved by the Government on the Khmer Rouge, "a history of Democratic Kampuchea, composed of 75 pages."
It was distributed to Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the history books of the Ministry of Education, designed for high schools, which contained less than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
As in most of Cambodia, the youth of Anlong Veng know only a few details of the Khmer Rouge, despite the links of the city to the regime.
Touch valeak, age 19, a student at the high school in Anlong Veng, stated that the new book was helping students understand a large part of their history.
But his parents have reacted with skepticism when he returned with the book to the home to investigate.
"My family rejects many parts of the Manual and the court", he says.
"they are suspicious because they do not know exactly how many people the Tribunal continue."
Such resistance has made the process of reconciliation, complex and difficult, said Sok Leang.
But public forums, the manual and the Tribunal are beginning to have an impact, at-il said.
However, the Khmer Rouge atrait retain a powerful here.
