Belarus agrees to give up its stock of weapons-grade uranium.
The Government of Belarus announced Wednesday that it would give up its stockpile of highly enriched uranium, a key component for nuclear weapons; that decision is part of a surprise victory for the campaign of President Obama to secure nuclear materials around the world
The agreement was disclosed in a joint communiqué issued after the Secretary of State Hillary Rodham Clinton met with the Belarusian Foreign Minister Sergei Martynov, on the sidelines of a Security Summit.
The US Government had tried for years to persuade the Belarus from highly enriched uranium and appeared to have reached the horizon last spring.
But US officials have told the Washington Post that some classified operations have been conducted with Belarus in the past two months to eliminate 187 pounds of weapons-grade uranium from a research centre of Belarus.
This paved the way for an agreement on Wednesday to remove the rest of the field of about £500, according to an official who spoke on the condition of anonymity because of the sensitivity of the issue.
The agreement appears to be one of the most important outcomes of the Nuclear Security Summit of 47 nations, organized at the initiative of Obama; when Belarus was excluded.
Apparently, it was good to get an invitation to the former Soviet Republic following the Summit in 2012.
"I am really fascinated by the fact that they want a seat at the Summit on Nuclear Safety and Nuclear Security Summit 2012."
"It proves that this process works," said Ken luongo, President of the partnership for global security, a group promoting nuclear security.
Clinton called the agreement "a very important step," conducted by Belarus.
Obama has pledged to Prague in April 2009 to secure all vulnerable nuclear material around the world within the next four years.
Since then, the United States Government has helped six countries to get rid of all its highly enriched uranium.
Belarus would be the seventh.
A dozen countries have done so under the administration of George W. Bush.
At the time of the Nuclear Security Summit of Obama, the Belarusian President Alexander Lukashenko, stated that the nation would never turn away from its uranium.
"We kept highly enriched uranium, hundreds of kilograms of which is essentially to weapons-grade uranium to low-enriched uranium," said Mr Lukashenko.
"It was our product... we will not manufacture dirty bombs, and we will sell it to anyone."
"We will use them for research purposes, this is it."
Belarus has brought the United States a few months; however, demonstrating the interest to reach an agreement.
The first implementation to eliminate uranium from Belarus in October, has been particularly complicated because the equipment had been spent slightly, officials have said.
It was loaded onto a special train has travelled more than 1,300 miles to a plant in Russia to be stored and eliminated, officials have said.
The second operation was completed Monday and was carried out by air, according to officials.
The US Government spent $13 million in its efforts, in large part, to replace the research facilities of Belarus with low-enriched uranium; unsuitable for weapons.
"a thorough organization and coordination have been implemented with a view to strengthening confidence", leading to the agreement signed by Clinton, said Andrew bieniawski, an official from the Department of Energy that specialized in reducing the global threat.
According to estimates of the Center for Non-proliferation Studies, James Martin, Belarus had this year at least 88 pounds of weapons-grade uranium, as well as hundreds of kilograms of highly enriched uranium.
Belarus seeks to eliminate its stockpiles by 2012, according to a joint statement.
Relations between Belarus and the United States have been strained for years, mainly because of the harsh suppression by Lukashenko on human rights.
But the statement on Wednesday suggested a potential revival.
“While welcoming the progress on these issues of global security, the United States and Belarus have recognized that greater respect for democracy and human rights in Belarus were essential to improve bilateral relations; and essential to the progress of the country and its citizens," she said.
