Red Bull triumph in F1 with a secret weapon for Siemens
A software creates improvements on cars in real time.
When Red Bull es entered the world of Formula 1 in 2004, its history in this sélecte universe of speed was marked by the surprise and success.
As a first time, nobody has taken into account the options of a new stable, who had just arrived, despite the upward trajectory of recent seasons, the past November, in the last phase of the championship they have all backed the triumph of Ferrari's Fernando Alonso.
Without lowering the skill as pilot of the champion, German Sebastien vette, the capacity of the Renault engine propelling his car, in the world of Formula 1 it spoke of the legend of the "secret weapon" that the multinational company Siemens was placed in the hands of Red Bull to transform it into a winning team.
It is in fact a powerful simulation software process that the German company has launched on the market in 2007 with the objectives of the distant automobilistique top-class.
Appointed PLM, this powerful tool technology has been used to create the chains of installation of manufacturing plants throughout the world, of energy, high-precision instruments.
The objective is to reproduce faithfully simulating the product or process before the building of a real manner, thus avoiding the defects and avoidable costs.
PLM has facilitated the development of cameras with canon, Sukhoi planes or more famous commercial vehicles for Nissan.
Siegfried russwurm, head of the Industrial division of Siemens, said the fact that the use of this technology in its plant in Formula 1 has led Red Bull to create and implement "in few hours, almost in real time," changes, changes and improvements detected during races and tests.
Russwurm explains that the stables of the year 1992 had an average of 10 technicians in their teams who was able to introduce a maximum of three or four improvements on vehicles each season.
In the Red Bull team are working today 180 young professionals of high qualifications, with powerful computer equipment to analyse and plan any kind of changes on the bolides.
The leader of the Siemens PLM software is able to analyse and improve all elements of bolides of Red Bull except the engine, which is the exclusive responsibility of Renault.
It amends the materials, fuel, aerodynamics and security features.
The changes may move the virtual reality simulator to reality in less than 24 hours, thanks to advanced systems of production, by laser autoclaves and high technology.
As the only limitation of this madness of technological development there is the $40 million that each team of Formula 1 can spend as limit each season to facilitate competition.
Red Bull has implanted the factory of high technology to create and produce its bolides in a town 50 miles from London.
These are two buildings where the visits, especially for journalists, are limited.
What is happening is considered "top secret".
The staff on duty in 580 people, take two pilots, the champion vettel and mark Webber.
The hero of the Formula 1 of Red Bull, without doubt, is the recent champion Sebastian vetell.
Among the great technological resources that the mark of energy drinks was placed at the service of its participation in the circuits, there are other hidden protagonists, whose work is invaluable and zero visibility.
The Director of Technology at the plant, Steve nevey, claims that five years ago, one could say that the progress of R + D in the case of cars racing made the 50 per cent of victories and the pilots were responsible for the rest.
Today, these percentages have changed and technology represents 85 per cent of success, while the pilot make the 15 per cent of the value added.
Nevey admit that both vettel and Webber will never be replaced by computer, because "they are unpredictable gladiators."
