Pakistan's nuclear programme is a major concern in the United States
Islamabad produced nuclear weapons at a faster pace than that other countries ".
The leaching of WikiLeaks confirms the connection between the Taliban and Pakistan.
The correspondence between the US Embassy in Pakistan and the Department of State of the United States percolates through the portal WikiLeaks confirms the enormous concern in Washington that Pakistan's nuclear programme.
To share the details illuminating and tasty offered on the content of the conversations and thoughts of American diplomatic representatives accredited in Islamabad, the documents reveal the fact that cooperation between the two countries in the area of nuclear security, instead of increasing, "fading" and that the volatile Asian countries producing nuclear weapons "at a faster rate than any other country in the world".
The peculiarity of the Pakistani nuclear program — the fact that weapons are not assemblies, but they are emmagasinnées by components to make difficult their destruction in case of attack - is one of the main reasons for concern in Washington.
This is as well as Ambassador to Pakistan, Anne W. Patterson, listed in a report prior to the visit of the former National Security Adviser, James Jones: "the proximity of some nuclear facilities in the territory under Taliban attack, the spread of nuclear materials including the rumour and the vulnerability of transport of nuclear materials.
The large number of persons involved in the nuclear weapons and missile programmes is envisaged, not only by the United States, but also by Russia, as proliferate and a reason to retain custody.
"Pakistan is hiring staff with strict religious beliefs to protect nuclear facilities; given the decline in educational and cultural levels, extremist organizations have more opportunities to recruit people who worked in the nuclear programmes or missiles," said the expert Yuri Korolyov, outside the Ministry of Russia during a meeting with his American counterparts.
The new documentation percolates through the portal of Julian Assange is cooperation increasingly reduced between the United States and Pakistan in the area of nuclear proliferation and the high degree of Pakistan nuclear Armas production.
A dispatch from the Embassy in May, which classifies as "frustrating" communication with Pakistan, maintains that: “transparency is frequently non-existent; the offers of aid remain unanswered or were eliminated".
In another message, Peter lavoy, National Intelligence Officer for South Asia, said that "despite the economic disaster, Pakistan has nuclear weapons at a faster rate than any other country in the world".
Ambassador Patterson also calls in Washington, during a visit to the army chief, General Ashfaq Kayani, to understand "very clearly" that "the army of Pakistan should end with the tacit support of terrorist groups".
