The leader of the democratic majority in the Senate, Harry Reid, announced Tuesday that he would ask for a vote to close debate "for the dream Act, which is why the initiative to legalize undocumented students could be passed from next Thursday in the Senate, although the most likely would be next week.
The Senate version of the dream Act or the act of American dream would legalize 800 000 young people who arrived in the United States before age 16, they stayed in this country in the past five years and they have been accepted by a higher education institution or by the army.
But the supporters need 60 votes to approve the initiative, for which reason they require the participation of a large number of Republicans, in times when the partisan organizations project protagonists intense lobbying to secure the approval of the law.
Democrats, the majority of which support the dream Act, have 58 seats.
However, at least one of them, Senator Ben Nelson of Nebraska, said he would vote in a Republican against and only expressed its support for the law, Richard Lugar of Indiana.
It is for this reason that the supporters of the dream Act require the vote of several Republicans if other Democrats will vote against the initiative.
Among the most Republicans are courted there, Maine senators Olympia Snowe and Susan Collins, and the outgoing Senator George Lemieux of Florida, which has supplemented the mandate Su Senator Mel Martínez.
Other Republicans who have in the past supported the dream Act are Orrin Hatch, of Utah, and Kay Bailey Hutchinson of Texas, but they have said that they would not support another opportunity.
Another Republican who has supported, John McCain, has not defined its position so far.
Even if the House of Representatives has a different version, analysts agree with the fact that the greatest obstacles to the dream Act are in the Senate.
