Rivers under strict surveillance
Several rivers remain under scrutiny because of the heavy rains that have hit several areas of the province since Tuesday.
A landslide occurred Wednesday afternoon, Shawinigan, in the mauricie.
Two houses have been evacuated in a preventive manner.
In the evening, another shift occurred in saint-lin-laurentides in lanaudière.
A road was collapsing.
From Tuesday to Wednesday evening, heavy rains have hit several parts, from 40 to 70 millimetres of rain.
20 to 40 millimetres of rain were expected by Thursday evening, according to the regions.
The areas north of the river and in the valley of the Outaouais were the most affected.
They could receive up to 100 millimetres of rain in total.
As the precipitation should be added to the melting of the snow already accumulated in certain sectors, it is feared the spillover of several rivers.
The flood alert warnings were issued Wednesday evening by the Quebec civil security for the rivers and ouareau achigan in lanaudière.
The rivers of the North, in the Saint Geronimo laurentides, and oak, in lotbinière, were also subject to flood vigils and remained under observation.
In the region of lanaudière, heavy rainfall led to the flooding of some lakes, sainte-julienne, sainte-marcelline-de-kildare and rawdon.
At saint-calixte, a temporary bridge was washed away because of heavy rains.
Ten homes had to be evacuated as a preventive measure.
In Outaouais, the spillover of some lakes has led to the closing of several roads, including in the municipality of mansfield-et-pontefract.
Civil security remains on alert and is monitoring the situation closely, said Annik Bouchard, Security Adviser.
The flood forecasting centre of Quebec has, for its part, issued Wednesday, warnings of heavy flooding in several rivers, including maskinongé, Asunción, ouareau, achigan, batiscan and wolves.
