A global plan to renovate lighting
The United Nations has proposed yesterday in Cancún a plan for renovation of the domestic, commercial and light industrial in 100 countries in order to achieve a reduction of greenhouse gases (GHGs), which represents almost a third of the additional reduction must be made to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
The ambitious plan is in the wake of major projects that the United Nations hoped to adopt at Cancún to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments by industrialized countries.
Under the plan filed yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs which monopolize yet of 50 to 70 per cent of the market were replaced by fluocompactes bulbs or, better, from light bulbs to light emitting diodes (LEDs or "led" in English), the bulk of the $1.8 billion tons (GT) GHG emissions on the planet to illuminate humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8 per cent of global emissions.
This is the equivalent of 70% of the emissions of global car park.
In Copenhagen last year, the major emitters, such as the US, China, Europe and other countries, including Canada, are engaged in voluntary reduction plans that should move the overall GHG emissions of 53 GT to 49 GT.
But it would be exempt from this assessment yet 5 GT in order to stabilize by 2020 the rise of climate change to 2 degrees Celsius to avoid it becoming out of control.
In the incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is lost as heat and the rest, or 5 per cent, a product of the light.
With fluocompactes bulbs, energy expenditure is reduced by 75 per cent, and with the new LED bulbs, it reduces the need for energy of two again.
Bulbs fluocompactes lasted an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those that launched the Philips manufacturing this week - that society has also participated in the study of the United Nations — have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a smouldering bulb, which gives an idea of the economy with an alternative plan that would apply to 100 countries.
These new bulbs can also operate with rhéostats in addition to emit very little heat.
And they do not contain any mercury.
Several experts expressed reservations about the location of fluocompactes bulbs because they contain mercury and that it must be eliminated as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless manufacturers are developing instructions.
But, says the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the bulb fluocompacte, but rather the coal-fired power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce electricity wasted in incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tons of Hg per year.
The report details the gains that would each country through the International Programme.
For example, Indonesia and worth $1 billion a year in electricity purchases and eight million tonnes of CO2 equivalent to 3.5 thermal power stations whose construction would cost $2.5 billion.
