The unemployment rate remained stable in France in the third quarter.
The unemployment rate in France within the meaning of the International Labour Office (ILO) remained stable at 9.3% in metropolitan France (9.7 per cent, including the overseas departments), showed the seasonally adjusted interim (CVS) published Thursday by INSEE.
The number of unemployed is 2,631 million in metropolitan France.
The data for the second quarter were confirmed at 9.3 per cent of the active population in metropolitan France and 9.7 per cent with the Dom.
About a year ago, the unemployment rate is seen rising by 0.1 point.
More broadly, 3.4 million people in metropolitan France did not work in the third quarter but wanted to work, whether or not they are available in the two weeks to work and that they are looking for a job.
The situation of young people in the labour market has deteriorated further, with a further increase in the unemployment rate to 24.2% in metropolitan France (+ 0.9 point to three months, + 0.5 point a year) and 25 per cent by including the Dom.
In the third quarter, 637 million young people aged 15 to 24 were unemployed within the meaning of ILO.
Older people are known for their part a slight rise in unemployment, to 6.4% in metropolitan France (+ 0.2 point to three months and a year), 482 000 people aged 50 or over, and 6.6 per cent with the Dom.
Only the 25-49 years have benefited from the stability of unemployment in the third quarter, to 8.3% in metropolitan France (-0.1 point on three months + 0.1 point a year) and 8.8 per cent in France.
INSEE publishes more monthly unemployment rate since 2006, after a controversy over its method of calculation.
Eurostat, the Statistics Agency of the European Union, continues to do so and announced Tuesday, a rate of 9.8 per cent for France (DOM included) in October after 9.9 per cent in September.
