Case Clotilde Reiss: the Élysée Palace has exaggerated the mediation of Syria
For more than ten months from July 2009 to May 2010, the fate of Clotilde Reiss, a young French researcher arrested in Iran for "espionage", held in suspense in France, put the diplomacy on alert, and deepened the deterioration of relations between Paris and Tehran.
All under the watchful eye of diplomats from the United States.
The American documents obtained by WikiLeaks and consulted by the World below reveal some of this crisis.
They describe how the Elysée explained its strategy to Americans, going so far as to give them advice for the treatment of their own crises "Hostages" in Iran (a small group of tourists).
They show how French officials have sought to convince Washington that the release of a young French woman had no counterpart for the release of Majid Kakavand, an Iranian detained in France and wanted by the United States for trafficking of materials for the benefit of the Iranian nuclear programme.
Finally, they place under a harsh spotlight how the French Presidency has sought to manipulate the media to give credence to the idea that the Syrian President, Bashar Al-Assad, has played a central role in the release of Clotilde Reiss.
In reality, there was nothing.
A diplomatic cable written on 12 August 2009 in Paris is entitled "Iran: comments on how to handle cases of hostages."
The Elysée Adviser for Strategic Affairs, François Richier, accompanied by the Director of the Quai d'Orsay in North Africa and the Middle East, Patrice Paoli, interact with the American diplomat Kathleen allegrone.
They explain the French approach.
They advise Americans to do the same to repatriate their own nationals used force in Iran.
"made of noise", they say, "martelez constantly" in the media the words "basic human rights", "innocence", "immediate release".
It is in order to embarrass the Iranian regime, sensitive to its image.
"just as the Iranians are asking you not to do so".
Because past attempts to discussions by discreet channels, "the silence will solve nothing," the Iranians are "masters in delaying tactics".
Mr. Richier adds that the detention of foreign nationals is "an Iranian tactic familiar: hostage-taking to political blackmail".
He announced that the release from prison of Clotilde Reiss, who will speak on 16 August, when it takes refuge in the French Embassy) "will require the payment to the Iranians for a large sum of money" (230 million euros in bail).
And he said that the Elysée anticipates other crises of hostages, a phenomenon which "will get worse".
The Iranians could "in the near future arrest another of some 1,800 French citizens living in Iran", he says.
August 28, 2009.
Clotilde Reiss was released from prison for 12 days, but remains blocked in Iran.
Information is disseminated: the Iranian Majid Kakavand, whom the US demanded the extradition for the illicit trafficking of sensitive electronic equipment to Iran, is released in Paris, on the decision of a judge.
The American Embassy, as many observers wondered about this unsettling coincidence.
For Washington, which Iranian clandestine networks stalking the acquisition of equipment for the nuclear programme, the expansion of Majid khakavand is bad news.
