No online games for young Koreans past midnight
The South Korean Government will adopt a "Cinderella" banning teenagers playing online games after midnight by blocking their access, said Government officials.
A bill will be submitted to Parliament in December to ask companies to online gambling to block access to the Games after midnight, young people under the age of 16 years, said representatives of the ministries of culture and family.
"many children play these games all night and were then difficult to study at school and have a normal life during the day."
"We believe that this law is needed to ensure their health and their right to sleep," said to AFP Jo NIR Ministerial, the officer in charge of the draft law.
Online games will be available at 6 a.m. the following morning.
Companies will have a year to prepare for the implementation of the law, he said.
The Government also plans to ask companies to limit the time daily access to these games for young people whose parents so request, added the official.
It will also be available to people who have been demanding free software to limit the time spent on the Internet.
South Korea is one of the most "connected" and newspapers are regularly made various related to the intensive use of the Internet.
The country is also the undisputed champion of the world competition online gambling.
In November, South Korea had won four gold medals at the World cyber Games, with 58 other nations.
