Euro: forced the ECB to maintain its purchases of government securities
The last meeting of the Board of Governors of the European Central Bank (ECB) of the year should be an opportunity to clarify the modalities of crisis or, at least, to announce the arrest of a number of unconventional monetary policy which must be achèver at the end of the year.
Sovereign debt crisis obliges the European emission Institute of Frankfurt will probably not afford to be so bold as to aggravate a situation more tense today on the European bond markets.
The political cost could be especially high.
Yesterday, at a press conference, French Finance Minister, Christine Lagarde, has welcomed the active role played by the ECB in favour of the resolution of the debt crisis of States in Europe.
She declined to say whether she believed that the Central Bank should do more, such as increasing its programme to purchase sovereign bonds.
"I reserve my reflection in my European partners (...)".
The day before, in Brussels, during his hearing by the Committee on Economic and Monetary Affairs of the European Parliament, the President of the ECB, Jean-Claude Trichet, has not shown more information about its intentions, merely indicate that the programme of buying government securities in the secondary market "continued" and that "we will see what we decide" at the meeting this Thursday.
One certainty: the ECB will keep its main interest rate unchanged at 1 per cent, its lowest level since May 2009.
In fact, purchases of Treasury bonds by the European Central Bank have doubled last week, nearly 1.35 billion euros.
And, according to the indiscretions of market operators, it would have made new purchases of securities Irish and Portuguese, yesterday.
In total, the central banks of the Eurosystem bought for 67 billion euros since May 2010.
Among the marketers, expectations of further purchases are no doubt (see page 29).
Economists do not expect significant change of course.
If the lending operations for more than three months have already disappeared from the arsenal of the ECB, the latter is still unlimited allowances in cash on generous and for periods from one week to three months.
Economists now expect that the scheme to be extended for a few months.
"I cannot imagine that it significantly alters its programme".
"otherwise it would be taking the risk of causing new tensions in the short term," said Michael Schubert, economist at Commerzbank.
"a gradual exit announced during the first quarter of 2011 seems more probable" anticipates Meanwhile Norbert bräms, economist at Sal.
Oppenheim.
In terms of its interventions on the government debt market, "the ECB should maintain a volume of these obligations to enliven a sluggish market," said Norbert bräms.
Given the importance of European banks' exposure to the markets of sovereign debt in the euro zone, the issue has no other choice than to maintain its presence in the market.
"It is a substitute for the lack of investors on the market and act so as to prevent a runaway returns paid on the most fragile states," reflected an important bond manager yesterday.
Because if interest rates are soaring, States will be more constrained to reduce their debt, if not stabilize.
The protection of the euro is the price.
In Italy, the Berlusconi Government made the back round
After a worrying week for Italy, the situation is a little more relaxed, yesterday, with the return of bond rate in 10 years.
A return to calm volatile.
At the end of a meeting with the Minister of the economy, the Presidents of the region said they had heard Giulio Tremonti called the situation "indecipherable" and expect a weekend "unpredictable", as he was then denied.
Tuesday, in any case, the gap with the German long rates had reached the peak of 210 basis points and the award of contracts to hedge against the risk of bankruptcy (CDS) had soared to 263 points, triggering a panic in Rome.
In the Council of Ministers, Silvio Berlusconi has pointed out that in Spain, the gap with the German rate was more than 400 basis points.
But his right arm, Gianni Letta, said he was "deeply concerned" by the "turbulence" and a possible contagion from Ireland.
"The good news is that Italy, third euro zone economy, is not like Greece or Ireland."
"The bad news is that it is like Portugal," said Irwin Stelzer, economist at the Hudson Institute.
Clearly, the problem is the lack of growth and weaker tax revenues that goes with them, leaving the State to run the risk of not being able to cover its financing needs.
The latest forecasts from Brussels was a cold shower for the Government.
Italian growth is now expected to 1.1 per cent in 2011 and to 1.4% in 2012... while the budget under consideration in the Senate respectively on table 1.3 per cent and 2 per cent.
In these circumstances, the European Commission, the public deficit will represent yet 4.3 per cent of GDP next year, compared with 3.9 per cent forecast by the Government) and 3.5 per cent in 2012 (2.7 per cent).
Hence the rumour of a new budget that could be put in place after the holidays, for an amount of EUR 7 billion.
"if necessary, new austerity measures will be taken," said Commissioner for Economic Affairs, Olli Rehn.
For the moment, Italy has the support of international institutions.
"the fundamentals of the economy are in order and its accounts are good, we have been saying for a long time," Arrigo Sadun, provides the Administrator of Italy at the International Monetary Fund in charge of Italy at the IMF.
"There is no problem in the immediate future, either in the short or long term, because despite its substantial debt (119.2 percent of GDP in 2011, ndlr), stabilization efforts made in Italy are lower than those made in other countries," said Pier Carlo padoan, Chief Economist at the OECD.
There remains the question of political instability.
On 14 December, Silvio Berlusconi takes a no-confidence vote in the Chamber of Deputies, following which early elections could be held in late March.
Then a period would not conducive to decision-making in the event of a serious crisis.
